       title="Finding the E-Test strip" id="Finding-the-E-Test-strip">

    <p>For our analysis algorithms to work E-Tests need to be annotated with the strip region. J-AST provides automated and interactive methods to achieve this task.</p>
    <chapter title="Automated E-Test strip detection">
        <note>Please ensure that your images follow the <a href="Image-preprocessing.topic">general expectations</a> of our algorithms and apply preprocessing if necessary.</note>
        <note>Please ensure that the <a href="Finding-the-plate.topic">plate region annotation is present</a>.</note>
        You can find the E-Test strip detection algorithm by first selecting the image(s) and then navigating to <ui-path>PROCESS | E-Test | Auto-detect ETest strip (v1)</ui-path>.
        The algorithm has one parameter:
        <deflist>
            <def title="Strip aspect ratio">
                The expected aspect ratio of the strip calculated as <code>[MAJOR_SIDE_LENGTH] / [MINOR_SIDE_LENGTH]</code>
            </def>
        </deflist>
        <img src="jast-etest-strip-v1.png" alt="Configuration dialog"/>
        <chapter title="Supported E-Test types">
            Due to the variety in E-Test strip designs, this algorithm is limited to handle only one specific type of E-Tests:
            <list>
                <li>Mostly upright; up to 40Â° tilting will likely work</li>
                <li>Bright strip with black text</li>
                <li>Black line surrounding the strip</li>
            </list>
            <img src="jast-strip-detection-requirements.png" alt="E-Test strip requirements"/>
        </chapter>
    </chapter>
    <chapter title="Manual E-Test strip detection">
        If the algorithms do not produce the expected results or if you prefer to do a manual annotation, you can use our interactive tool.
        To open it, select the image and click the <control>Edit</control> button for the strip annotation on the right-hand side.
        <img src="jast-strip-edit.png" alt="Edit E-Test strip"/>
        To lean more about the interactive editor, follow <a href="Manual-annotations.topic">our guide</a>.
    </chapter>
</topic>